	<string>$publish $workflow webfonts # Workflow to ... download WOFF fonts from Google Fonts.

**The Google Web Fonts service** provides content for your stylesheets needed to **remotely include various formats of the fonts you wish to use** on your websites. But what if you don't want to rely on the Google Servers but **have these web fonts served locally from your own server?** Here's how:

1. **Go to Google Web Fonts** and **select the font you want** by clicking the *Add to Collection* button. Remember to **select all the formats** you want.
2. **Navigate to the *Use* page** by clicking on the *Use* tab within the *collections* popup at the bottom of the page.
3. From the *standard* tab, **copy the href source**:

	![][1]

		http://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Quattrocento+Sans:400,700,400italic,700italic

4. **Navigate to this URL to find the CSS** required to source the web-fonts directly from Google Web Fonts

        @font-face {
            font-family: 'Quattrocento Sans';
            font-style: italic;
            font-weight: 700;
            src: local('Quattrocento Sans Bold Italic'), local('QuattrocentoSans-BoldItalic'), url(http://themes.googleusercontent.com/static/fonts/quattrocentosans/v6/8N1PdXpbG6RtFvTjl-5E7XqmoHPhRtDxMEWFjaribELr7w4p9aSvGirXi6XmeXNA.woff) format('woff');
         } 
         
5. **Navigate to the url source of each WOFF font** to download the font locally to your machine.

		http://themes.googleusercontent.com/static/fonts/quattrocentosans/v6/8N1PdXpbG6RtFvTjl-5E7XqmoHPhRtDxMEWFjaribELr7w4p9aSvGirXi6XmeXNA.woff

6. **Rename the files** to something sensible:

		mv 8N1PdXpbG6RtFvTjl-5E7XqmoHPhRtDxMEWFjaribELr7w4p9aSvGirXi6XmeXNA.woff Quattrocento_bold_italic.woff
		
7. **Change the permissions of the font** to make it usable:

		chmod 755 Quattrocento_bold_italic.woff
		
8. **Serve the font locally on you own server** to include and use the font on any of your websites.

